====================================================================
SPOT release 2.0.0, static executables and shared libraries 
README file
December 4, 2007
====================================================================

This file contains information about the files contained in this
software release, and explains how to run a simple test of the 
software.  

====================================================================
New in this release:

  * getting started guide
  * expanded and updated user guide
  * directory of examples
  * reorganization of software
    - refactoring of detection and consequence assessment code
    - extraction of health impacts consequences into a separate
       code repository
  * addition of new health impacts
    - population dosed impact (pd)
    - impact measures for 'detected' impacts (e.g. dtd, dpe)
  * revision of integer programming solver to
       minimize a 'detected' impact given a constraint on the number
       of failed detections.
  * update of the PICO solver, using new incumbent heuristics


====================================================================
Known issues:

   * The heuristic solvers cannot minimize 'detected' impacts yet

====================================================================
Release contents:

Executable files:
	* aggregateImpacts-- creates smaller impact files by aggregating locations
	* evalsensor	  -- computes objectives given sensor placements
        * filter_impacts  -- a script to filter impacts
	* PICO 		  -- integer programming solver
	* randomsample	  -- local search heuristic for basic problems
	* setupIPData	  -- prepares input for integer programming solver
	* sideconstraints -- local search heuristic for side constraints
	* scenarioAggr	  -- produces scenario-aggregated impact files
	* sp   		  -- driver script for sensor placement runs
	* sp_tracer	  -- driver script for sensor placement tracer studies
	* tevasim	  -- ANL/UC "threat simulation output" file generator
	* tso2Impact	  -- impact file generator
	* ufl	  	  -- the Lagrangian solver

====================================================================
Testing the release:

If you have chosen a Linux release with shared libraries, you must
know that the libraries were built with the assumption that they
would reside in the directory /usr/local/lib.  Create that directory
if you don't already have it, and copy all of the .so files in the
"lib" directory to it.  Then add "/usr/local/lib" to your 
LD_LIBRARY_PATH environment variable.  Detailed instructions are at
the end of this file if you're not familiar with these ideas.
	
You can test the software by running the test scripts in
the "test" directory.  A simple one is "test1a".  If you look at
this script, you will see it does the following:

1. Run tevasim to create .tso files from a simple network (Net3.inp)
and from a threat scenario file (test1.tsg).  (If you normally use
TEVA to generate this information, you do not need tevasim other
than when running "test1a".)

2. Run tso2Impact to create impact files from the .tso files.

3. Execute the sp script, which will
   - run setupIPData to create the data for the solver
   - run the PICO solver on the data, using a model in the /mod directory
   - run the evalsensor program to evaluate the solver output

The sp script and the other programs mentioned are described
in detail in the User's Guide in the doc directory.

You can see the output of the test by looking at the test1.log file.

To execute a test script, just type its name:

On Linux:

./test1a
./test1a_l
./test1r

On Windows:

test1a
test1a_l
test1r

---------------------------------------------------------------------
TESTING 2.0 FUNCTIONALITY

---------------------------------------------------------------------
SHARED LIBRARIES ON LINUX 

You can ignore this section if you are not using a release
tar file containing shared libraries.

The shared libraries must be installed in /usr/local/lib.  As
superuser, make the directory if you don't already have it.

su -
<enter root password>
mkdir /usr/local/lib
exit

Unpack the release.  (You can be an ordinary user to do this.)

tar xvfz teva-spot-2.0.0-linux32-gcc4.1.2-shared.tar.gz

Again as superuser, copy the libraries to /usr/local/lib:

su -
<enter root password>
cd {path where you installed the tar file}
cd teva-spot-2.0.0-linux32-gcc4.1.2-shared/lib
cp *.so /usr/local/lib
exit

Now (as an ordinary user), add /usr/local/lib to your 
LD_LIBRARY_PATH environment variable, which specifies
the path that will be searched for shared libraries when you 
run an executable:

export LD_LIBRARY_PATH=$LD_LIBRARY_PATH:/usr/local/lib
cd teva-spot-2.0.0-linux32-gcc4.1.2-shared/test
test1a

The "export" command works in some shells, but not in others.
If it doesn't work for you, try "setenv" instead:

setenv LD_LIBRARY_PATH /usr/local/lib:${LD_LIBRARY_PATH}

